Sometimes it happens that the new form which is due to Analogy exists side by side with the ι form which is the result of Phonetic Law, e. g. Σωκράτην side by side with Σωκράτη. Where there is a similarity of mean- ing between one word and another or a group of words, the tendency is by analogy to make them resemble one another¹ in form. Thus by phonetic law εῐ-μί takes the place of ε’σ·μι, side by side with εἀ-τί, but instead of εῖ-μέι like εῖ-μί we find εἀ-μίν on the analogy of ιά-τί and ιά-τέ. Analogy then leads men to systematise the different forms of words and arrange them in symmetrical groups. A few instanees from different languages will illustrate this.
